The Central Bank of Nigeria (CBN) has disclosed that at least 1.14 million farmers have benefited from its Anchor Borrowers Programme (ABP) since 2015. The CBN Director, Corporate Communication Mr. Isaac Okorafor said this at the 2019 Abuja International Trade Fair. Mr. Okorafor was represented by his Deputy Director, Mrs. Veronica Aqua said, “Another major intervention programme is the Anchor Borrowers’ Programme (ABP), designed and launched in 2015 to finance smallholder farmers and create economic linkage between the farmers and commodity processors/millers. OVER 5,000 NIGERIAN MEN HAVE  OVERCOME POOR BEDROOM PERFORMANCE SYNDROME DUE TO THIS BRILLIANT DISCOVERY “A total of 255 private and 14 State Government anchors had participated in the scheme as at June, 2019 in addition to 1,140,854 farmers producing 17 different agricultural commodities had benefited from the Scheme with a view to increasing production and enhancing capacity utilisation in agro-processing Industry,” he said. The ABP is one of the 29 CBN intervention programmes targeted at various stakeholder groups such as farmers, women, youth, small and medium enterprises. Speaking on another intervention in the agric space, the Commercial Agricultural Credit Scheme (CACS), the Director explained that the programme which commenced in 2009 is to fast-track the development of the agricultural sector and has provided credit facilities to commercial agricultural enterprises at a single digit interest rate. “A total of 1,132,260 jobs along the various agricuttural value chains had so far been created and capacity utilisation of the agro ailied companies have also been increased” with the programme he said.  CBN disburses N44bn to farmers, recovers N50bn CBN’s Anchor Borrowers’ Programme: A game changer in Nigeria’s rice production CBN defends position on agriculture financing, MSMEs